{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517023"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:49:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:49:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12752"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12752"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.26,0.03,0.56,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5199"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79089"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5199"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12752"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64441"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1892"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8821"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9155"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26946"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79089"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman is admitted to hospital after noticing some painful \u0022black spots\u0022 on her calves. She cannot recall when they started but knows she has had a \u0022patchy rash\u0022 on her legs for the last year.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer history includes end-stage renal failure secondary to focal segmental glomerulosclerosis, for which she has had two kidney transplants. Her current kidney transplant is failing and so she is being worked up to start haemodialysis with AV fistula formation. She has also had a partial parathyroidectomy. Additionally, she has atrial fibrillation. Her current medications include warfarin, tacrolimus, mycophenolate, and prednisolone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the black spots on her calves are approximately 2 cm in diameter. The skin around her calves looks normal otherwise. Her laboratory investigations are shown:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: 12 ml/min (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 1243 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea: 27.2 mmol/L (2.7-8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcium: 1.96 mmol/L (2.1-2.6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhosphate: 3.58 mmol/L (0.75 - 1.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the likely diagnosis for the \u0022black spots\u0022 on her calves?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lipodermatosclerosis","Ecthyma gangrenosum","Diabetic dermopathy","Calciphylaxis (calcific uremic arteriolopathy)","Livedo reticularis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThese \u0022black spots\u0022 in a patient with end-stage renal failure and a history of a rash (i.e. livedo reticularis) indicate the diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalciphylaxis (\u003C/strong\u003Ecalcific uraemic arteriolopathy\u003Cstrong\u003E). \u003C/strong\u003ECalciphylaxis refers to the calcification of the media of arteries, which leads to vascular occlusion due to vascular and soft tissue calcification, eventually causing gangrene of the skin. It is often preceded by livedo reticularis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalciphylaxis is associated with advanced hyperparathyroidism (although it can also occur in the absence of severe hyperparathyroidism).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWarfarin is commonly used as an anticoagulant in patients with end-stage renal failure as it is hepatically eliminated. Most direct acting oral anticoagulants (apixaban, etc.) are rarely eliminated and are contraindicated in patients with end-stage renal failure. However, warfarin decreases the production of vitamin K-dependent regeneration of matrix Gla protein. This protein is involved in preventing vascular calcification. Thus, warfarin can lead to calciphylaxis in a patient with an already high predisposition to vascular calcification from hyperparathyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment of calciphylaxis is IV sodium thiosulfate, which is a calcium ion binder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalciphylaxis has a high 1 year mortality of 45-80%. Most patients die due to sepsis from infected gangrenous wounds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEcthyma gangrenosum\u003C/strong\u003E results in painless haemorrhagic pustules that evolve into black necrotic ulcers. It is commonly seen in critically ill, immunocompromised and neutropenic patients co-infected with Pseudomonas bacteraemia. It mainly affects the anogenital area and armpits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has no history of diabetes to indicate \u003Cstrong\u003Ediabetic dermopathy, \u003C/strong\u003Eor of venous insufficiency to suggest \u003Cstrong\u003Elipodermatosclerosis.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calciphylaxis refers to the calcification of the media of arteries, which leads to vascular occlusion due to vascular and soft tissue calcification, eventually causing gangrene of the skin.","Calciphylaxis is associated with advanced hyperparathyroidism and can be exacerbated by medications like warfarin.","Warfarin can lead to calciphylaxis by decreasing the production of vitamin K-dependent proteins that prevent vascular calcification."],"references":["Gallo Marin B, Aghagoli G, Hu SL, Massoud CM, Robinson-Bostom L. Calciphylaxis and Kidney Disease: A Review. Am J Kidney Dis. 2023 Feb;81(2):232-239. doi: 10.1053/j.ajkd.2022.06.011. Epub 2022 Aug 12. PMID: 35970430. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35970430/","Gaisne, R., P\u00e9r\u00e9, M., Menoyo, V. et al. Calciphylaxis epidemiology, risk factors, treatment and survival among French chronic kidney disease patients: a case-control study. BMC Nephrol 21, 63 (2020). https://doi.org/10.1186/s12882-020-01722-y Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32101140/","Westphal SG, Plumb T. Calciphylaxis. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30085562. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30085562/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64441"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12752"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64441"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T14:43:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T14:45:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5199"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79089"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":nu